<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        3D Viewer
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to open the 3D viewport, move around the map, and control which layers are shown.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Opening the 3D Viewport
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The
        <Bold>3D Viewport</Bold> gives you a live three-dimensional visualisation of the
        current map so you can inspect heights, buildings, objects, textures, and roof areas
        from an in-world perspective.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        To open it, press
        <Bold>Ctrl+3</Bold> from the Map Editor. This launches the 3D Viewer
        window and loads the current map using the same editor state you are already working with.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>The 3D Viewer is intended as a visualisation tool for checking your work from
another angle. It updates in real time, so changes made in the Map Editor are reflected in the
3D view while both windows are open.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        Layer Visibility
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The 3D Viewer inherits the same layer visibility state as the main Map Editor when it is
        opened. This means the layers you currently have enabled in 2D are passed through into the
        3D view automatically.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Once the viewer is open, you can directly control the displayed layers using the
        <Bold>Layer checkboxes</Bold> on the right-hand side of the 3D Viewer window.
        These let you quickly show or hide supported map elements without needing to switch back
        to the main editor.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This makes it easy to inspect the map in different ways - for example, viewing only
        buildings and roof surfaces, or hiding textures so the structure of the map is easier to
        read.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Camera Controls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The 3D Viewer uses keyboard controls for movement and looking around the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Moving the Camera
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>W</Bold> = move forward
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>S</Bold> = move backward
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>A</Bold> = move left
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>D</Bold> = move right
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>E</Bold> = move upward / elevate the camera
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Q</Bold> = move downward / lower the camera
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>



    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Looking Around
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use the
        <Bold>Arrow keys</Bold> to rotate the camera view and look around the map.
        This allows you to examine structures, terrain, and object placement from different angles.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/3dviewer.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2A3A" BorderBrush="#4A4A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#B0B0E0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Navigation advice:</Run>
                <Run>Use </Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">WASD</Run>
                <Run> and </Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Q/E</Run>
                <Run> together to position the camera, then use the </Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Arrow keys</Run>
                <Run> to line up the angle you want. This is especially useful when checking roof
heights, building placement, and the overall feel of a street or courtyard.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Live Updates and Performance
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The 3D Viewport updates in real time as the map changes, allowing you to inspect edits as
        they happen. This is useful for quickly checking how the map looks from a gameplay-style
        perspective.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Because the viewer is rendering a 3D representation of the map, updates may take time to
        appear - especially on larger maps or when many layers are visible at once.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For best results, do most of your detailed editing work in the 2D Map Editor first, then
        open the 3D Viewer when you want to review the result. This usually gives the smoothest
        experience and avoids unnecessary redraw overhead while you are making frequent changes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2F2A" BorderBrush="#8A6A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#F0D0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Performance note:</Run>
                <Run>If the 3D view feels slow to refresh, close the 3D Viewer while doing heavy
2D editing and reopen it afterwards with </Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Ctrl+3</Run>
                <Run> when you are ready to inspect the map again.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Worked Example
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A common workflow is to build or adjust part of the map in 2D, then open the 3D Viewer to
        verify the result from a playable angle.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 1:</Bold> In the main Map Editor, enable the layers you want to inspect, such
        as textures, buildings, objects, or roof tiles.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 2:</Bold> Press
        <Bold>Ctrl+3</Bold> to open the 3D Viewport.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 3:</Bold> Use
        <Bold>WASD</Bold> to move across the map and
        <Bold>Q</Bold> /
        <Bold>E</Bold>
        to raise or lower the camera.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 4:</Bold> Use the
        <Bold>Arrow keys</Bold> to look around and inspect the area from
        different angles.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 5:</Bold> Use the layer checkboxes on the right-hand side to refine what is shown
        until you have the clearest view of the feature you want to check.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Tips
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use
                <Bold>Ctrl+3</Bold> to quickly open the 3D Viewer whenever you want a
                fast visual check of the current map.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>The 3D Viewer starts with the same layer visibility state as the Map Editor,
                so set up your 2D layers first if you already know what you want to inspect.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use the right-hand layer checkboxes to simplify the scene when too much is
                visible at once.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use
                <Bold>Q</Bold> and
                <Bold>E</Bold> often when checking rooftops, upper
                walkways, and building heights.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>If performance drops during heavy editing, close the 3D Viewer and reopen it
                after your 2D work is done.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
